Ùª­jAttributesÙ¯‚€öpExtended SummaryÙ¯‚Ù¹‚Ù§yThis is an implementation of the algorithm detailed in . The basic idea is to construct a meta-graph of bridge-ccs, connect leaf nodes of the trees to connect the entire graph, and finally connect the leafs of the tree in dfs-preorder to bridge connect the entire graph.€ögMethodsÙ¯‚€öeNotesÙ¯‚‰Ù¹‚Ù§x¤Input: a graph G. First find the bridge components of G and collapse each bridge-cc into a node of a metagraph graph C, which is guaranteed to be a forest of trees.€Ù¹‚Ù§x~C contains p "leafs" --- nodes with exactly one incident edge. C contains q "isolated nodes" --- nodes with no incident edges.€ÙÁÙÅ‚Ù¹‚ƒÙ§x%Theorem: If p + q > 1, then at least Ù¥oceil(p / 2) + qÙ§j edges are€Ù¹‚Ù§xDneeded to bridge connect C. This algorithm achieves this min number.€Ù¹‚Ù§xbThe method first adds enough edges to make G into a tree and then pairs leafs in a simple fashion.€Ù¹‚Ù§yÓLet n be the number of trees in C. Let v(i) be an isolated vertex in the i-th tree if one exists, otherwise it is a pair of distinct leafs nodes in the i-th tree. Alternating edges from these sets (i.e.  adding edges A1 = [(v(i)[0], v(i + 1)[1]), v(i + 1)[0], v(i + 2)[1])...]) connects C into a tree T. This tree has p' = p + 2q - 2(n -1) leafs and no isolated vertices. A1 has n - 1 edges. The next step finds ceil(p' / 2) edges to biconnect any tree with p' leafs.€Ù¹‚Ù§x²Convert T into an arborescence T' by picking an arbitrary root node with degree >= 2 and directing all edges away from the root. Note the implementation implicitly constructs T'.€Ù¹‚Ù§xThe leafs of T are the nodes with no existing edges in T'. Order the leafs of T' by DFS prorder. Then break this list in half and add the zipped pairs to A2.€Ù¹‚Ù§xAThe set A = A1 + A2 is the minimum augmentation in the metagraph.€Ù¹‚Ù§x.To convert this to edges in the original graph€öpOther ParametersÙ¯‚€öjParametersÙ¯‚Ù°ƒaGnNetworkX graphÙ¹‚Ù§tAn undirected graph.€öfRaisesÙ¯‚€öh